5":"circa 1485","1449":"1449","Brokenhaugh, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Warden, Northumberland, England":"Warden, Northumberland, England","Brokenhaugh, Warden, Northumberland, England":"Warden, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1449–1485":"1449–1485","1440–1485":"1440–1485","1485–1552":"1485–1552","1469":"1469","1455":"1455","1552":"1552","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","about 1485":"about 1485","1449":"1449","Brokenhaugh, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Warden, Northumberland, England":"Warden, Northumberland, England","Brokenhaugh, Warden, Northumberland, England":"Warden, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Norton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places so called, from Old English <i>north</i> ‘north’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. In some cases it is a variant of   Norrington  .","Irish: altered form of   Naughton  , assimilated to the English name (see 1 above).","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of some similar (like-sounding) original Ashkenazic surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Norrington","meanings":["English:","(southeastern): from Norringtonend in Redbourn (Hertforshire), Northingtown Farm in Grimley (Worcestershire), or Norrington in Alvediston (Wiltshire). All three names are from Old English <i>north in tūne</i> ‘to the north of the village’.","possibly a variant of <b>Northampton</b>, a habitational name from the city of this name, which was named with Old English <i>north</i> ‘north’ + <i>hām</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘homestead, home farm’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":6,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes J Norton was born in 1449, in Warden, Northumberland, England. She married John Allen in 1469, in Warden, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1485, in her hometown, at the age of 36."},"et":{"1449–1485":"1449–1485","1440–1485":"1440–1485","1485–1552":"1485–1552","1469":"1469","1455":"1455","1552":"1552","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","about 1485":"umbes 1485","1449":"1449","Brokenhaugh, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warden, Northumberland, England":"Warden, Northumberland, England","Brokenhaugh, Warden, Northumberland, England":"Warden, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1449–1485":"1449–1485","1440–1485":"1440–1485","1485–1552":"1485–1552","1469":"1469","1455":"